A joint recurrent registration-segmentation network is used to compute OAR segmentations on a given target (MRI or CBCT) image volume. The recurrent registration network (RRN), indicated as $g$ and the recurrent segmentation network (RSN), indicated as $s$ are implemented using a 3D-CLSTM that extends 2D-CLSTM previously developed for non-medical images. The input to the network are a pair of source $\{x_{m}, y_{m}\}$ (images with segmentations) and target $x_{f}$ images from which target segmentation $y_{f}$ is computed. RRN produces progressively warped images and contours $\{x_{m}^{i}, y_{
m}^{i}\}$ in N CLSTM steps, where 1 $\leq$ i $\leq$ N. RSN uses N+1 CLSTM steps, because the first CLSTM step (i=0) directly processes the source image and its segmentation with the target image ($\{x_{m},y_{m},x_{f}\}$). The RSN inputs for steps $i \geq 1$ use outputs of RRN from the intermediate CLSTM steps $i$ and $x_{f}$, ($\{x_{m}^{i}, y_{m}^{i}, x_{f}\}$). The RRN produces a deformably warped image $x_{m}^{t}$ and a segmentation $y_{m}^{t}$ aligned to the spatial coordinates of the target image $x_{t}$. RSN is used to further improve the segmentations on the target image by using the RRN outputs as anatomic and shape priors. Our results show accuracy improvement when using RSN over just the RRN segmentations.
